00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:39.850
Smoothing.

00:00:39.850 --> 00:00:43.900
This sort of sequence began
with the optimal allocation

00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:48.070
of risk bearing and what
you would see in the data.

00:00:48.070 --> 00:00:53.440
We saw the benchmark was doing
well in many but not all cases.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:58.780
And there were some examples
where coefficients on income

00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:03.550
were higher and for
certain occupations

00:01:03.550 --> 00:01:05.725
and certain types of income.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:13.710
Then we took that same
benchmark still clinging to it

00:01:13.710 --> 00:01:17.273
and looked at a whole different
kind of data, production data.

00:01:17.273 --> 00:01:18.690
And we're going
to come back to it

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:22.290
next time when we talk
about labor supply.

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:25.080
But while we're on the subject
of consumption and consumption

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:28.110
smoothing, I thought
it would be good to go

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:30.030
through some
alternative models that

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:34.680
are widely used and
different data sets

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:41.910
and give you a sense of what
people do in the literature.

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:47.400
So a lot of this has to do with
the permanent income model.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:51.580
It's just kind of the
basic sort of thing

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:55.210
that people rely on and
fall back on constantly

00:01:55.210 --> 00:01:58.655
or say consumption smoothing
over the life cycle.

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:03.880
These markets are not complete.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:08.680
They shut down a lot of the
risk contingencies allowing

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:15.610
households to trade only in risk
free bonds or maybe have some

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:19.240
other savings account which
cannot go below zero or limited

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:21.970
credit.

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:23.740
The papers were going
to cover, first one,

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:27.550
there's one by
Kaplan and Violante,

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:30.250
which is going to look at
the degree of consumption

00:02:30.250 --> 00:02:34.780
through smoothing from this SIM,
which is Standard Incomplete

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:35.730
Market model.

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:37.150
They're also going
to simulate it.

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:43.000
So that's using it
two purposes there.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.990
And we're going to
look at smoothing

00:02:46.990 --> 00:02:49.990
through the lens of that
model and in the data

00:02:49.990 --> 00:02:52.980
against permanent shocks
and transitory shocks.

00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:57.610
This is a language we have
not been using so far.

00:02:57.610 --> 00:03:04.650
But it is standard language
in this other literature,

00:03:04.650 --> 00:03:08.250
and look at how smoothing varies
against these various shocks

00:03:08.250 --> 00:03:11.400
[? varies ?] over
the life cycle.

00:03:11.400 --> 00:03:13.740
The Violante paper
and others draw

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:16.470
on this [? Blundell, ?]
Pistaferri,

00:03:16.470 --> 00:03:20.340
and Preston method,
which is looking

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:23.835
at consumption and income data.

00:03:27.450 --> 00:03:31.080
And in fact, there is not
typically a very long time

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:33.930
series in the US to use.

00:03:33.930 --> 00:03:37.770
The best is a PSID , which
used to only have food.

00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:40.950
So part of this paper is
about how to splice together

00:03:40.950 --> 00:03:46.170
two different databases
to create a longer panel

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:48.270
and measure the degree
of smoothing in the data.

00:03:49.335 --> 00:03:52.500
Then we'll move to
Deaton and Paxson, which

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:56.340
is the same overall
topic but actually

00:03:56.340 --> 00:03:57.780
quite interesting
because they're

00:03:57.780 --> 00:04:03.450
going to be looking more at
the variance of consumption

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:08.740
in cross sections, which is
an implication of the models.

00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:10.410
But you don't need these panel.

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:14.100
You just need a bunch of cross
sections for various years.

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:16.510
So effectively, if
it's representative,

00:04:16.510 --> 00:04:18.110
you can track people by age.

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:24.090
And again, they do that
through a permanent income

00:04:24.090 --> 00:04:27.600
model, a buffer stock model,
a model with borrowing

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:32.070
constraints, as well as in the
background, the full insurance

00:04:32.070 --> 00:04:36.870
model, and relate it
to things in the data.

00:04:36.870 --> 00:04:41.160
Then there's this Campbell
and Deaton paper, which

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:44.330
is about excess smoothness.

00:04:44.330 --> 00:04:49.580
And I kind of smile every
time I see this title because

00:04:49.580 --> 00:04:54.290
from the standpoint of the
permanent income model,

00:04:54.290 --> 00:04:57.305
you should respond to
shocks to permanent income.

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:03.800
And they see in the
data that consumption

00:05:03.800 --> 00:05:06.190
is smoother than that.

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:09.550
So they call it
excess smoothness.

00:05:09.550 --> 00:05:11.800
My smiles come from
the fact that they

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:15.850
haven't considered the full
risk-sharing benchmark, which

00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:19.190
may not fit
perfectly well either

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:21.910
but may be part of the
explanation in the background.

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:28.430
And then finally, we have
this Krueger and Perri

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:33.990
paper, which looks at
the US and Italian data.

