00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:23.200
So what's the problem?

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:26.950
In the US as I was saying,
we need longitudinal data

00:06:26.950 --> 00:06:28.900
on consumption and income.

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:34.660
And on consumption, we need
a comprehensive measure.

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:39.410
No one's been gathering
these kinds of data.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:41.950
So how do people cope with it?

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:44.725
They could use the PS
and just look at food.

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:51.070
Or they could look exclusively
at the Consumer Expenditure

00:06:51.070 --> 00:06:55.090
Survey, which has a whole
bunch of line items.

00:06:55.090 --> 00:06:58.647
But people are not in that
sample for more than three

00:06:58.647 --> 00:06:59.355
or four quarters.

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:09.960
Or you could sort of basically
create these synthetic cohorts

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:13.415
by sort of extrapolating
and merging,

00:07:13.415 --> 00:07:15.915
which is increasingly a common
way to deal with the problem.

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:27.430
Another way to sort of
think about this upfront

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:33.250
is these models are
making a distinction

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:37.270
between permanent and transitory
shocks, but we only see income.

00:07:37.270 --> 00:07:40.810
We don't see each of these
different kinds of shocks

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:42.590
individually.

00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:45.608
So what to do about that?

00:07:45.608 --> 00:07:47.650
You could ignore it and
just look at the response

00:07:47.650 --> 00:07:49.540
to total income
change, which is kind

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:52.380
of what we've been doing,
actually, in the development

00:07:52.380 --> 00:07:52.965
data sets.

00:07:55.790 --> 00:07:59.280
You could use
proxies for permanent

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:00.660
versus transitory shocks.

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:02.970
For example, disability
might rightly

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:06.150
be thought of as a
rather permanent shock.

00:08:06.150 --> 00:08:08.070
Short-term unemployment
might be thought

00:08:08.070 --> 00:08:10.380
of as a transitory shock.

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:16.230
So that's another way to
try to deal with a problem.

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:20.450
And then there's sort of a
public finance tax literature.

00:08:20.450 --> 00:08:22.610
Different people
assume different things

00:08:22.610 --> 00:08:24.170
about different kinds of taxes.

00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:26.150
Some tax is assumed
to be permanent,

00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:28.850
others assumed to be transitory.

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.550
And then you kind of see how
households react to that.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:45.640
So the benchmark model
people use for saying,

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:49.570
quote, "How much insurance is
there actually in the data?"

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:54.820
Is this Blundell,
Pistaferri, Preston paper,

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:56.650
I doubt if we'll
get to that today.

00:08:56.650 --> 00:08:59.080
It is in the
appendix, so I have it

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:02.980
in the slides, time permitting.

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:07.450
But it's basically covariance
decomposition of the income

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:10.580
and consumption process.

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:13.750
So that's the quote
view of the data.

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:16.300
Then for the models, you start
with the standard incomplete

00:09:16.300 --> 00:09:20.710
markets model, assuming no
access to contingent claims

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:24.310
but allowing some
kind of insurance

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:26.600
through buying
and selling bonds.

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:31.300
Now let me pause for a second,
just in case it's not clear.

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:35.350
And this literature uses
confusing language, actually.

00:09:35.350 --> 00:09:39.400
If you thought about a household
in isolation or a business,

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:41.720
they have ups and
downs of income.

00:09:41.720 --> 00:09:45.850
And it's clear that by
saving, you kind of smooth off

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:49.210
the peaks so that
higher income does not

00:09:49.210 --> 00:09:51.220
make its way into consumption.

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:55.480
And likewise, in the valleys,
when income is really low,

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:58.180
you can carry forward
that savings to that

00:09:58.180 --> 00:10:02.050
spot or borrow, which
makes the valley less deep.

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:04.940
So consumption is smooth
to a large degree,

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:10.360
but not completely against
these fluctuations.

00:10:10.360 --> 00:10:11.890
What's the difference
between that

00:10:11.890 --> 00:10:14.830
and the full risk-sharing model?

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:17.590
The idea there is that you
don't have-- not everyone's

00:10:17.590 --> 00:10:21.430
facing idiosyncratic
and transitory shocks

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:23.180
at the same time.

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:26.560
So as in the Rocky
Mountains diagram,

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:29.560
peaks and valleys come
at different stages.

00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:34.570
And even after you act as if a
household would do everything

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:37.750
that it could on its
own, you're still

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:40.550
left with this
asynchronous timing.

00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:43.060
So what the risk-sharing
model is basically doing

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:47.260
is transferring consumption
around in the cross-section

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:50.388
to get even flatter consumption.

00:10:50.388 --> 00:10:52.180
And the only thing that
would be left then,

00:10:52.180 --> 00:10:54.130
if you believe the full
risk-sharing model,

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:57.220
are those shocks that
basically somehow get

00:10:57.220 --> 00:11:00.610
left in aggregate consumption
after all that smoothing.

00:11:00.610 --> 00:11:02.630
The only part of the
peaks and valleys

00:11:02.630 --> 00:11:06.070
that's common across all the
households would be left.

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:09.050
And everything else
would be flattened out.

00:11:09.050 --> 00:11:12.880
So this literature,
it's true that you

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:15.070
can do an enormous
amount of smoothing

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:17.630
by borrowing and lending.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:19.600
But it is not true
that you can do

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:23.230
everything that would
be possible with greater

00:11:23.230 --> 00:11:24.870
amounts of insurance.

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:28.510
Anyway, so they start
with the standard--

00:11:28.510 --> 00:11:31.150
note the word
standard-- it's standard

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:35.140
for the certain branches
of the macro literature,

00:11:35.140 --> 00:11:38.770
incomplete markets literature.

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:41.140
You may or may not
put on a lifecycle.

00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:44.800
To be realistic, you'd
say, the household faith

00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:47.440
sees a stochastic
probability of dying.

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:53.687
And that makes them
more and more vulnerable

00:11:53.687 --> 00:11:56.020
as they get older and older,
in some sense, because they

00:11:56.020 --> 00:11:58.090
can't smooth that out.

00:11:58.090 --> 00:12:01.900
Or they have to front-load
stuff into savings

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:05.750
to be able to cope with
fluctuations as they get older.

00:12:05.750 --> 00:12:08.815
So it does matter whether the
horizon is infinite or finite.

00:12:12.102 --> 00:12:13.810
There are permanent
and transitory shocks

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:15.490
to earnings while they earn.

00:12:15.490 --> 00:12:19.470
But if it's the life
cycle model as in the US,

00:12:19.470 --> 00:12:21.370
where there is
literally retirement,

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:23.830
then earnings go to zero.

00:12:23.830 --> 00:12:27.430
You may have some income
stream from social security,

00:12:27.430 --> 00:12:31.120
and these guys
will load that in.

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:32.950
And you may have
some assets you've

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:38.530
put in a pension fund, which has
kind of an insurance component

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:42.010
to it, in the sense that
you're getting an income

00:12:42.010 --> 00:12:48.250
stream from the pension but
averaging over the mortality

00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:49.790
risk in the population.

00:12:49.790 --> 00:12:53.170
So there's a bit of insurance
in the standard pension funds.

00:12:57.010 --> 00:13:00.510
Another version has
borrowing limits.

00:13:00.510 --> 00:13:03.000
There's something called
the natural borrowing

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:04.500
limit or the zero.

00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:06.240
Zero is obvious.

00:13:06.240 --> 00:13:07.830
You can't borrow
anything at all,

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:10.290
or you'll put just
a bound, can borrow

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:13.650
10% of your assets
or your income.

00:13:13.650 --> 00:13:17.490
The natural borrowing limit
is something like this.

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:19.200
You always have to
repay your debt.

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:20.910
So you can't borrow
more than what

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:24.180
you could repay in the
worst possible income

00:13:24.180 --> 00:13:26.790
realization in the future.

00:13:26.790 --> 00:13:29.580
And then it matters a
lot what you're assuming

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:31.140
about the income process.

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:34.320
If there's a small
chance of a zero income,

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:37.720
and your debt is due
in that situation,

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:39.820
then effectively you
can't borrow at all.

00:13:39.820 --> 00:13:42.870
So it's a rather
stringent criterion.

00:13:48.270 --> 00:13:49.770
And then they'll take--

00:13:49.770 --> 00:13:54.500
you'll see Kaplan and
Violante then take the model.

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:59.130
And they simulate, hence
the SIM, artificial data

00:13:59.130 --> 00:14:00.245
from the model itself.

00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:05.990
There's two reasons
for doing that.

00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:11.050
First of all, this Blundell,
Pistaferri, Preston paper

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:12.700
is doing something
with the data.

00:14:12.700 --> 00:14:15.670
It's not a direct
look at the data.

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:19.100
But the summary statistics
come from this BPP algorithm.

00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:20.590
So they want us--

00:14:20.590 --> 00:14:23.230
if you want a common ground,
which is what's in the data

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:27.010
through BPP, then let's look at
the data generated by the model

00:14:27.010 --> 00:14:30.040
through BPP and compare
apples to apples.

00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:38.380
On the other hand, when you have
a model and you simulated it,

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:39.640
that is the reality.

00:14:39.640 --> 00:14:43.540
You know exactly what
the economy is like.

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:46.270
So they also use this--

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:49.720
pick up distortions,
where BPP is

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:53.050
kind of giving you a summary
statistic of the degree

00:14:53.050 --> 00:14:55.480
of insurance, which is
not actually what's going

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:57.460
on in the underlying model.

00:14:57.460 --> 00:15:00.640
So they use this to
look at the biases

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:03.030
or what can generate the bias.

00:15:03.030 --> 00:15:06.580
The intuition there is
pretty straightforward.

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:12.460
Zero borrowing or limits to
borrowing are like a corner.

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:14.830
And you're either constrained
or you're not constrained,

00:15:14.830 --> 00:15:19.270
so that's a non-linearity,
whereas BPP algorithm

00:15:19.270 --> 00:15:22.510
is basically linear.

00:15:22.510 --> 00:15:28.000
So the distortions get
introduced by the more likely

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.780
you are to be hitting corners,
the higher the distortion is.

00:15:36.390 --> 00:15:41.630
So the standard
incomplete market model

00:15:41.630 --> 00:15:43.490
generates an
insurance coefficient

00:15:43.490 --> 00:15:50.590
for transitory shocks of
94% in the natural borrowing

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:54.430
constraint economy, or 82% in
the zero borrowing constraint

00:15:54.430 --> 00:15:56.200
economy.

00:15:56.200 --> 00:15:58.190
That's a coefficient
for insurance,

00:15:58.190 --> 00:16:00.713
so that's a good thing.

00:16:00.713 --> 00:16:02.380
Be careful you don't
get flipped around,

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:06.340
because we've been looking at
the degree to which consumption

00:16:06.340 --> 00:16:09.170
fluctuates with income, so you
start to think high numbers

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:09.670
are bad.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:12.510
But this is 1 minus that.

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:15.610
So for them, high
numbers means insurance,

00:16:15.610 --> 00:16:17.500
which means a good thing.

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:20.590
Those are numbers,
94, 82, compared

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:24.850
to the BPP run on the
actual data, which is 95.

00:16:24.850 --> 00:16:28.580
So that's an excellent fit.

00:16:28.580 --> 00:16:30.880
But when they look at
the insurance coefficient

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:35.170
for permanent shocks,
it's 22% or 7%,

00:16:35.170 --> 00:16:38.800
depending in the model what
you assume about credit.

00:16:38.800 --> 00:16:42.790
But in the actual
data, it's 36%.

00:16:42.790 --> 00:16:46.390
And here already you're
seeing this recurrent theme

00:16:46.390 --> 00:16:49.000
that there's better
smoothing against even

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:55.150
the permanent shocks in the
data than these models allow.

00:16:55.150 --> 00:16:58.840
And then if you looked
at the life cycle

00:16:58.840 --> 00:17:01.450
through the lens
of the model, you

00:17:01.450 --> 00:17:05.770
would see better insurance
as people get older.

00:17:05.770 --> 00:17:08.290
But in the data, it's not there.

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:10.450
There's no age
profile in the data.

00:17:13.230 --> 00:17:15.099
So the model-- another
way to say this,

00:17:15.099 --> 00:17:16.839
is generating too
much consumption

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:20.530
smoothing for the older
workers, relative to the data,

00:17:20.530 --> 00:17:23.290
or too little
smoothing for workers

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:26.470
in the early stage
of their lifecycle,

00:17:26.470 --> 00:17:28.600
relative to the data.

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:31.720
If you're skeptical, you've
got to be skeptical about BPP

00:17:31.720 --> 00:17:33.460
because it's supposed
to be, quote,

00:17:33.460 --> 00:17:37.180
a "fact" that they're finding.

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:41.380
We'll look at some of that
data though through the lens

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:43.060
of the cross-sectional
distributions

00:17:43.060 --> 00:17:44.680
when we get to
Deaton and Paxson.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:47.980
And then you'll kind
of see something else.

00:17:47.980 --> 00:17:52.510
And I haven't thought about
how to reconcile that yet.

00:17:52.510 --> 00:17:57.580
So what I said about the
reliability, when they simulate

00:17:57.580 --> 00:17:59.680
and use the data
from the model, it's

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:03.850
fine for the transitory
shocks, largely.

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:06.430
But it tends to underestimate
the true coefficient

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:09.550
for the permanent shocks.

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:12.490
That's actually making
this situation worse

00:18:12.490 --> 00:18:14.980
because then the
BPP measure, which

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:16.930
shows good insurance for
the permanent shocks,

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:21.550
is a lower bound estimate of the
actual insurance in the data,

00:18:21.550 --> 00:18:23.310
so there's an even
greater divergence.

00:18:23.310 --> 00:18:23.837
Yes?

00:18:23.837 --> 00:18:25.670
AUDIENCE: Can I just
make sure I understood?

00:18:25.670 --> 00:18:29.520
So in the data, we
see changes in how

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:31.275
I smoothed over the lifecycle.

00:18:31.275 --> 00:18:33.810
But in the model, we
don't see any changes?

00:18:33.810 --> 00:18:35.280
Or have I got it
wrong way around?

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:37.530
ROBERT TOWNSEND: No, it's
almost the other way around.

00:18:37.530 --> 00:18:38.420
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:40.850
So the model we see it as
[? profile, ?] but in real life

00:18:40.850 --> 00:18:41.450
we don't see--

00:18:41.450 --> 00:18:43.543
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:18:43.543 --> 00:18:45.960
AUDIENCE: So that seems kind
of counterintuitive, I guess,

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:46.640
to us.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:51.063
Wouldn't we expect-- maybe I'm
thinking of a different method.

00:18:51.063 --> 00:18:52.980
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah,
the problem is taking--

00:18:57.190 --> 00:19:00.810
the model is
generating differences

00:19:00.810 --> 00:19:03.610
by age because of
the life cycle.

00:19:03.610 --> 00:19:06.720
But the data does not show that.

00:19:06.720 --> 00:19:12.540
So that's why you get this
sort of odd-looking statement

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:15.600
that looks like it's more
criticism of the model.

00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:18.710
But it's of the model
relative to the flat data.

00:19:18.710 --> 00:19:21.030
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
once we [INAUDIBLE]..

00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:22.680
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
Someone once said,

00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:24.960
if the data don't
fit the model, it

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:26.550
must be something
wrong with the data.

00:19:30.090 --> 00:19:32.190
So we're feeling
at pressure here.

00:19:35.340 --> 00:19:36.090
I didn't say that.

00:19:42.730 --> 00:19:47.200
How can you get more
smoothing to generate

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:55.395
less sensitivity of consumption
to these permanent shocks?

00:19:59.940 --> 00:20:03.310
Because again, there's-- it
seemed to get turned around

00:20:03.310 --> 00:20:04.420
so easily.

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:07.310
There's more smoothing in
the data than in the models.

00:20:07.310 --> 00:20:10.480
So you want the model to allow
more smoothing to catch up

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:12.020
to the data.

00:20:12.020 --> 00:20:15.640
And one thing you could
do is give households

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:18.710
a little more information
about the future.

00:20:18.710 --> 00:20:19.720
And then the idea--

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:20.830
it's a smoothing model.

00:20:20.830 --> 00:20:23.680
So if they know things are
going to get better or worse,

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:27.790
they can take actions now
and adjust consumption.

00:20:27.790 --> 00:20:30.430
So the overall profile
that would result

00:20:30.430 --> 00:20:34.630
would be smoother if they
could anticipate future income,

00:20:34.630 --> 00:20:42.610
rather than having to react
to sudden information.

00:20:42.610 --> 00:20:46.930
And a close cousin of
that is to move away

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:54.010
from some random walk, to put in
some serially correlated income

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:55.690
process.

00:20:55.690 --> 00:20:58.660
And that, actually,
does a better job

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:02.300
in getting the model
to match the data.

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:12.010
As I said, so far in this class,
we haven't talked too, too much

00:21:12.010 --> 00:21:15.890
about these income processes.

00:21:15.890 --> 00:21:20.030
But it's really front
and center here.

00:21:20.030 --> 00:21:23.760
What you assume about an
income process, is it IID?

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:26.780
Is it autoregressive,
for that matter,

00:21:26.780 --> 00:21:27.980
with high frequency data?

00:21:27.980 --> 00:21:30.590
What about the seasonality
and everything?

00:21:34.190 --> 00:21:37.920
That makes you aware of
both the great strength

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:40.770
and vulnerability of the
risk-sharing model, which

00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:45.270
says it doesn't matter what
time it is or what state it is.

00:21:45.270 --> 00:21:48.960
Just add up total consumption
and smooth it out.

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:53.040
There's a fixed static
rule for allocating risk.

00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:56.550
There could be predictable
periodic seasonal fluctuations

00:21:56.550 --> 00:21:58.530
or trends in income.

00:21:58.530 --> 00:22:00.780
It doesn't matter for
the risk-sharing model.

00:22:00.780 --> 00:22:07.454
But here with incomplete
models, it matters much more.

00:22:07.454 --> 00:22:09.835
AUDIENCE: You say that
two is better than one.

00:22:09.835 --> 00:22:11.715
If it's AR, it's
going to be better

00:22:11.715 --> 00:22:13.560
than predicting the future.

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:19.012
But AR, to a degree, is also the
ability to predict the future.

00:22:19.012 --> 00:22:20.720
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah,
it's very related.

00:22:20.720 --> 00:22:23.090
AUDIENCE: So there's
something else from the AR

00:22:23.090 --> 00:22:24.585
that's making it better?

00:22:24.585 --> 00:22:26.460
ROBERT TOWNSEND: I guess
there are other ways

00:22:26.460 --> 00:22:27.990
to predict the future.

00:22:27.990 --> 00:22:31.080
Even if the process itself
is not autoregressive,

00:22:31.080 --> 00:22:33.850
you could get signals about what
it's going to be in the future.

00:22:33.850 --> 00:22:35.800
AUDIENCE: That's
not as good as--

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:37.800
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's
what the claim is, yeah.

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:41.320
That's what they find.

00:22:41.320 --> 00:22:43.510
So here's the model, finally.

00:22:43.510 --> 00:22:45.560
There is no aggregate
uncertainty.

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:53.610
Agents work until retirement,
but they don't die then.

00:22:53.610 --> 00:22:56.670
There's a probability
[? z ?] of surviving.

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:03.530
This is, I guess, retirement
is a really bad thing

00:23:03.530 --> 00:23:07.000
because if you
don't retire, you're

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:10.000
going to live with
probability 1.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.540
So anyway, this is
a simplification.

00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:21.310
So they only start using these
actuarial tables after age

00:23:21.310 --> 00:23:25.900
60 or 65, whatever they
put in for retirement age.

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:29.110
So it's maximizing
discounted expected utility,

00:23:29.110 --> 00:23:31.970
common utility function.

00:23:31.970 --> 00:23:33.950
We've been doing
a lot of that too.

00:23:33.950 --> 00:23:37.940
Beta is the standard discount
rate. [? Z ?] is this--

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:41.270
you only get the utility
if you're alive, basically.

00:23:41.270 --> 00:23:44.330
So that's a standard adjustment
to the discount rate.

00:23:44.330 --> 00:23:49.860
The income process
is a bit complicated.

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:55.560
First of all, there is a
possible nonstochastic trend,

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:59.240
sort of the deterministic
part, which could move income

00:23:59.240 --> 00:24:04.170
along with T. And then you
have income, quote, "standard."

00:24:04.170 --> 00:24:05.690
Here's the decomposition.

00:24:05.690 --> 00:24:09.800
Income is equal to z, which
is this permanent thing,

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:13.470
in this case, entirely a
random walk, and epsilon,

00:24:13.470 --> 00:24:18.170
which is the IID
transitory shock.

00:24:18.170 --> 00:24:21.410
So these papers use
different notation.

00:24:21.410 --> 00:24:25.530
And this paper, z, is permanent,
and epsilon is transitory.

00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:27.110
And eta is another shock.

00:24:27.110 --> 00:24:29.930
And that's the shock to
permanent income, basically.

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:38.320
So in expectation, you expect
your income to be what it was.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:40.240
You expect the permanent
part of your income

00:24:40.240 --> 00:24:42.790
to be exactly what
it was last period.

00:24:42.790 --> 00:24:48.600
But this thing will
move that around.

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:50.820
And then these have variances--

00:24:50.820 --> 00:24:54.140
sigma eta, sigma epsilon.

00:24:54.140 --> 00:24:59.670
The budget constraint, again,
is like this bond, which you may

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:02.190
or may not be able to short.

00:25:02.190 --> 00:25:07.730
So you've got your
assets from last period.

00:25:07.730 --> 00:25:11.240
That's earning interest,
plus your income.

00:25:11.240 --> 00:25:14.510
So this is like your
disposable income,

00:25:14.510 --> 00:25:18.100
which you can spend on
consumption and assets,

00:25:18.100 --> 00:25:20.290
going forward.

00:25:20.290 --> 00:25:21.280
Watch the subscript.

00:25:21.280 --> 00:25:22.330
It'll drive you crazy.

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:24.220
It does me.

00:25:24.220 --> 00:25:28.360
This is dated t plus 1.

00:25:28.360 --> 00:25:31.210
But it's decided on a t,
and consumption is also

00:25:31.210 --> 00:25:32.770
decided on a t.

00:25:32.770 --> 00:25:34.270
So in some of these
formulas, you're

00:25:34.270 --> 00:25:37.330
going to see a mysterious
interest rate adjustment.

00:25:37.330 --> 00:25:43.630
And it has to do with this sort
of convention of the timing.

00:25:43.630 --> 00:25:46.840
This looks the same,
except as I said,

00:25:46.840 --> 00:25:50.120
it's like a pension
fund in your assets.

00:25:50.120 --> 00:25:52.495
So effectively,
this gets adjusted.

00:25:55.060 --> 00:25:59.590
It's not like everyone has
their own individual retirement

00:25:59.590 --> 00:26:02.410
account, which you draw down.

00:26:02.410 --> 00:26:04.600
There's a pool of money there.

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:08.330
Some people continue to
live, and some don't.

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:12.280
And so those-- in other words,
if you're, quote, "lucky,"

00:26:12.280 --> 00:26:14.080
and you keep living,
you could actually

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:18.730
draw more from the fund
than what you put in there.

00:26:18.730 --> 00:26:21.895
And this is a very convenient
way to kind of adjust.

00:26:26.280 --> 00:26:30.510
Oh, and if you're retired
you get your social security

00:26:30.510 --> 00:26:32.940
benefits.

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:35.400
They're going to put
some numbers in here

00:26:35.400 --> 00:26:39.480
from the life cycle
literature and other sources,

00:26:39.480 --> 00:26:42.480
using various US data sets.

00:26:42.480 --> 00:26:45.490
And I'm not going to
dwell on the numbers.

00:26:45.490 --> 00:26:51.050
But this is a classic
picture of the life cycle.

00:26:51.050 --> 00:26:56.940
So here are the
earnings going up.

00:26:56.940 --> 00:27:02.370
You guys are down here
somewhere, on average.

00:27:02.370 --> 00:27:06.780
You can expect to do
better eventually.

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:10.800
And then you get to be 60,
and it doesn't go to zero.

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:14.490
That's if you were a US citizen,
that's where you start drawing.

00:27:14.490 --> 00:27:17.070
Actually, you could
just be an immigrant.

00:27:17.070 --> 00:27:22.080
You start drawing social
security benefits.

00:27:22.080 --> 00:27:29.310
With this profile, you try
to keep consumption steady.

00:27:29.310 --> 00:27:30.690
It's not completely flat.

00:27:30.690 --> 00:27:32.760
It just looks flat
relative to everything else

00:27:32.760 --> 00:27:33.570
on this diagram.

00:27:33.570 --> 00:27:36.810
It's actually
increasing somewhat.

00:27:36.810 --> 00:27:41.082
But the goal of the
life cycle smoothing

00:27:41.082 --> 00:27:44.340
is to try to have more or
less steady consumption.

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:51.270
Again, this is-- there
are two lines here.

00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:53.995
There's a natural borrowing
constraint and zero borrowing

00:27:53.995 --> 00:27:54.495
constraint.

00:27:54.495 --> 00:27:57.270
It doesn't make too much
different for consumption.

00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:04.080
I guess here the zero
borrowing constraint

00:28:04.080 --> 00:28:05.790
looks more constraining.

00:28:05.790 --> 00:28:09.510
So when you're young,
expecting on average higher

00:28:09.510 --> 00:28:13.110
future income, you might
want to borrow against that

00:28:13.110 --> 00:28:15.240
and repay the debt later.

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:17.760
But you hit one or the
other of these constraints,

00:28:17.760 --> 00:28:19.710
so you can't do that too much.

00:28:19.710 --> 00:28:28.030
Of course, the gorilla in the
room is this wealth profile.

00:28:28.030 --> 00:28:31.320
And that's where all the
action is, basically.

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:35.910
In fact, you're basically
over the life cycle,

00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:40.608
accumulating and then
deaccumulating wealth.

00:28:40.608 --> 00:28:43.085
That's what's keeping
consumption steady.

00:28:43.085 --> 00:28:45.660
And remember, when income
goes to virtually zero,

00:28:45.660 --> 00:28:47.190
apart from social
security, you've

00:28:47.190 --> 00:28:49.020
got to live off the
interest in your--

00:28:51.990 --> 00:28:56.700
you have social security, plus
the adjusted actuarial interest

00:28:56.700 --> 00:28:57.840
off the pension fund.

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:01.500
And that's typically
a lot smaller flow

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:04.230
than was your previous income.

00:29:04.230 --> 00:29:07.650
So you need a ton
of assets to be

00:29:07.650 --> 00:29:10.770
able to survive into old age.

00:29:10.770 --> 00:29:13.785
This is drawn out, looks
like to 90 something, 95.

00:29:23.390 --> 00:29:24.770
That could have
been shown first,

00:29:24.770 --> 00:29:28.250
but that's kind of a summary
of the life cycle model

00:29:28.250 --> 00:29:31.940
and what Kaplan and
Violante are doing,

00:29:31.940 --> 00:29:38.450
and they're generating these
smoothing statistics from date

00:29:38.450 --> 00:29:40.010
by date with shocks.

00:29:40.010 --> 00:29:43.730
But this is the overall
pattern you would see.

00:29:43.730 --> 00:29:48.560
Let's go to Deaton and Paxson
for a very different look at it

00:29:48.560 --> 00:29:53.580
through the lens of
these cross sections.

00:29:53.580 --> 00:29:56.450
The starting point, again, is
that with a permanent income

00:29:56.450 --> 00:29:59.480
hypothesis, consumption
of each person

00:29:59.480 --> 00:30:04.820
should basically
follow a random walk.

00:30:04.820 --> 00:30:09.650
Again, the idea is
you should basically

00:30:09.650 --> 00:30:12.035
be eating at the level
of your permanent income.

00:30:14.690 --> 00:30:16.880
And when you're permanent
income is shock,

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:18.290
then your consumption is shock.

00:30:25.090 --> 00:30:27.100
But the implication
that consumption

00:30:27.100 --> 00:30:31.510
follows a random walk
means, basically, you'll

00:30:31.510 --> 00:30:34.150
see the equations for it.

00:30:34.150 --> 00:30:37.330
Date by date by
date, you get hit

00:30:37.330 --> 00:30:41.110
with positive or negative
shocks and their IID.

00:30:41.110 --> 00:30:44.230
So basically, some
people have their ups

00:30:44.230 --> 00:30:46.510
and other people
have their downs.

00:30:46.510 --> 00:30:49.290
So you start getting
this fanning out.

00:30:49.290 --> 00:30:51.880
And then you go-- then you take
the cohort that is still all

00:30:51.880 --> 00:30:52.690
alike.

00:30:52.690 --> 00:30:54.220
Go one more period.

00:30:54.220 --> 00:30:55.510
They have ups and downs.

00:30:55.510 --> 00:30:57.580
Those guys fan out a bit.

00:30:57.580 --> 00:31:00.520
So the cross-sectional
distribution

00:31:00.520 --> 00:31:02.350
just keeps getting
fatter and fatter

00:31:02.350 --> 00:31:04.300
with bigger and bigger tails.

00:31:06.820 --> 00:31:10.660
So all of the slides,
basically, are

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:15.190
going to be about this
increasing consumption

00:31:15.190 --> 00:31:17.065
inequality in the cross-section.

00:31:17.065 --> 00:31:20.560
They measure it by
the standard deviation

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:24.610
of the log of consumption,
age group by age group.

00:31:28.690 --> 00:31:34.750
But again, if you thought
about full risk-sharing,

00:31:34.750 --> 00:31:37.650
you get this dramatic contrast.

00:31:37.650 --> 00:31:41.340
At least for the cases where
people have uniform risk

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:45.030
aversion and so on, then
we know that what pins down

00:31:45.030 --> 00:31:47.880
the level of your
consumption, on average, is

00:31:47.880 --> 00:31:49.710
going to be your Pareto weight.

00:31:49.710 --> 00:31:53.310
And you kind of have
those fixed at t equals 0.

00:31:53.310 --> 00:31:55.800
That's going to
fix the intercepts.

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:59.220
And your consumption might
fluctuate with aggregate shocks

00:31:59.220 --> 00:32:01.680
around that, but it's
not going to move

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:04.060
with age or anything else.

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:06.030
So basically, the
cross-sectional dispersion

00:32:06.030 --> 00:32:10.930
of consumption does not increase
in the full risk-sharing model.

00:32:10.930 --> 00:32:15.270
But you will see that in the
data, depending on the country,

00:32:15.270 --> 00:32:15.980
it does happen.

00:32:23.220 --> 00:32:27.930
You have to be a little
mindful of going back and forth

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:33.090
between this cross-sectional
age-dependent inequality,

00:32:33.090 --> 00:32:38.470
and inequality for the
economy as a whole,

00:32:38.470 --> 00:32:40.810
because demographics can shift.

00:32:40.810 --> 00:32:44.650
Even if you give
me someone's age,

00:32:44.650 --> 00:32:47.560
and I'll tell you sort of what
the cross-sectional dispersion

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:51.015
is in the population, when you
have demographics going on,

00:32:51.015 --> 00:32:52.390
you may have an
increasing number

00:32:52.390 --> 00:32:57.380
of young people or old people,
depending on the economy.

00:32:57.380 --> 00:33:01.690
So you're basically taking
an age-weighted average

00:33:01.690 --> 00:33:05.560
as the demographics shift, and
that will shift inequality.

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:07.000
So an issue in
this literature is

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:08.950
how much of aggregate
inequality can

00:33:08.950 --> 00:33:13.780
be explained by these kinds
of life cycle smoothing

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:18.820
considerations, and
how much by baby booms

00:33:18.820 --> 00:33:21.700
versus fertility
drops and all of that.

00:33:27.570 --> 00:33:33.250
So this is kind of nice because
they have the US, Britain,

00:33:33.250 --> 00:33:37.360
and cross sections, which
are three countries that

00:33:37.360 --> 00:33:43.180
have a quite ample amount of
cross-sectional consumption,

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:46.840
for that matter,
also, income data.

00:33:46.840 --> 00:33:50.980
They're going to use 47
annual surveys spread out

00:33:50.980 --> 00:33:54.350
over the three
countries and look

00:33:54.350 --> 00:33:59.450
at the implications of
these models for the kind

00:33:59.450 --> 00:34:02.000
of cross-sectional
inequality and see

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.580
what it takes to explain it.

00:34:04.580 --> 00:34:06.875
So how does this work exactly?

00:34:10.300 --> 00:34:13.210
So we want to follow
cohorts over time.

00:34:13.210 --> 00:34:17.230
We cannot follow an
individual person over time,

00:34:17.230 --> 00:34:20.230
because it's not panel data.

00:34:20.230 --> 00:34:24.920
But you make the assumption
that, for example,

00:34:24.920 --> 00:34:33.179
if you see a bunch of
31-year-olds in 1976 in Taiwan,

00:34:33.179 --> 00:34:35.310
you're getting a good
summary statistic

00:34:35.310 --> 00:34:36.840
of the cross-sectional
dispersion

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:39.150
