00:40:50.270 --> 00:40:51.530
Let's start with the basics.

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:58.330
Here is basically Hall's
permanent income implication

00:40:58.330 --> 00:41:00.070
for consumption.

00:41:00.070 --> 00:41:04.990
Consumption should
essentially be a random walk.

00:41:04.990 --> 00:41:06.640
And it's only moving
around because

00:41:06.640 --> 00:41:11.830
of the innovations or the
shock to permanent income.

00:41:11.830 --> 00:41:15.700
I think that was
[? JPE, ?] 1970.

00:41:15.700 --> 00:41:19.330
The dates here, I think
it was in the [? JPE. ?]

00:41:19.330 --> 00:41:20.320
There are assumptions.

00:41:20.320 --> 00:41:23.170
This isn't always true.

00:41:23.170 --> 00:41:29.110
He assumed quadratic utility,
additive preferences,

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:35.640
discount rates equal to
interest rates, and, I think,

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:38.100
another life cycle.

00:41:38.100 --> 00:41:39.900
This is supposed to
be an innovation,

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:47.610
so for every person
at least, there's

00:41:47.610 --> 00:41:50.760
no covariance between
lagged consumption

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:52.470
and this innovation,
because it wasn't

00:41:52.470 --> 00:41:54.460
supposed to be predictable.

00:41:54.460 --> 00:41:57.750
That's the same conversation,
just how much, if anything,

00:41:57.750 --> 00:41:59.360
you see about the future.

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.250
Here, zero is seen.

00:42:02.250 --> 00:42:05.130
So I described this in words.

00:42:05.130 --> 00:42:10.830
But basically, if it were
stable like this on average,

00:42:10.830 --> 00:42:15.670
then consumption dispersion
shouldn't be changing.

00:42:15.670 --> 00:42:18.670
But you're just
layering on repeatedly,

00:42:18.670 --> 00:42:21.100
shock after shock after shock.

00:42:21.100 --> 00:42:24.800
So with that zero
covariance assumption,

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:28.270
the variances are increasing
by the variance of that [? u ?]

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:29.200
t shock.

00:42:39.700 --> 00:42:44.980
And basically, if you started
plotting these distributions,

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:47.230
the one at t is going
to have fatter tails

00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:49.660
than the one at t minus 1.

00:42:49.660 --> 00:42:53.950
So t minus 1, [? quotient, ?]
first order stochastically

00:42:53.950 --> 00:42:54.730
dominates.

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:03.000
You have to be a little
bit careful throughout all

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:04.920
of this stuff.

00:43:04.920 --> 00:43:06.750
You think about
things in the point

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:09.780
of view of a person
tracking a person over time.

00:43:09.780 --> 00:43:12.540
But that statement
about c t and [? u t ?]

00:43:12.540 --> 00:43:17.310
is actually a statement about
the cross section, as well as

00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:19.240
the intertemporal dimension.

00:43:29.460 --> 00:43:32.340
This model typically
didn't have taste shifters

00:43:32.340 --> 00:43:35.310
or heterogeneous preferences.

00:43:35.310 --> 00:43:37.440
You can put those things in.

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:41.630
Depending on how you put them
in, it does make a difference.

00:43:41.630 --> 00:43:45.010
Arguably, if we hadn't done
the demographics right,

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:46.590
but they claim--

00:43:46.590 --> 00:43:50.060
Deaton and Paxson
claim for Taiwan,

00:43:50.060 --> 00:43:54.530
then you kind of need
preference shocks to help

00:43:54.530 --> 00:43:56.090
with the observed dispersion.

00:44:02.190 --> 00:44:05.125
Here is the basic sort
of budget equation again.

00:44:14.770 --> 00:44:16.460
And I'm afraid each
one of these papers

00:44:16.460 --> 00:44:19.080
kind of has a different
convention about the timing.

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:23.610
So it's really kind of hard
to keep tracking and track it.

00:44:23.610 --> 00:44:31.170
But basically, you have
sources and uses of money.

00:44:31.170 --> 00:44:34.640
The sources are previous
assets plus interest.

00:44:34.640 --> 00:44:37.560
The uses are-- source
also is income,

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:38.890
and the use is consumption.

00:44:38.890 --> 00:44:42.800
And then what you don't
spend accumulates on

00:44:42.800 --> 00:44:45.000
to the next period.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:52.880
If you do do the life cycle
with a terminal date, for sure,

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:58.900
say, age 99 or
whatever you want,

00:44:58.900 --> 00:45:03.190
then you can actually
get a formula closed form

00:45:03.190 --> 00:45:07.400
for consumption, under these
other maintained assumptions.

00:45:07.400 --> 00:45:12.760
And basically, it's
kind of saying,

00:45:12.760 --> 00:45:15.790
consumption ought to equal
something about the return

00:45:15.790 --> 00:45:19.060
stream through the
interest rate on assets,

00:45:19.060 --> 00:45:23.230
and something about the
forward-looking part, which is

00:45:23.230 --> 00:45:25.900
expected future income shocks.

00:45:25.900 --> 00:45:33.640
So this kind of helps you see
how future things are already--

00:45:33.640 --> 00:45:35.140
if this is going
to be very high,

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:38.800
for example, then this
is already going up.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:40.900
So it's kind of smooth against--

00:45:40.900 --> 00:45:43.750
or low, vise versa.

00:45:43.750 --> 00:45:46.510
It's tricky with a finite
horizon and a cap t

00:45:46.510 --> 00:45:51.520
because there is a coefficient
premultiplying this,

00:45:51.520 --> 00:45:53.410
but it's for that
reason, basically.

00:45:53.410 --> 00:45:59.320
Obviously, the closer you
are to the end to cap t,

00:45:59.320 --> 00:46:01.090
the less smoothing
you can accomplish.

00:46:01.090 --> 00:46:04.480
And that's inherited
into this formula.

00:46:06.990 --> 00:46:07.490
Yep?

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:10.175
AUDIENCE: The shocks here
are IID all the time?

00:46:10.175 --> 00:46:11.050
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yes.

00:46:14.090 --> 00:46:19.455
Well, the shock to
permanent income is IID.

00:46:22.460 --> 00:46:25.240
But permanent income is
an autoregressive process.

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:37.695
The standard incomplete markets
model had an infinite horizon.

00:46:37.695 --> 00:46:39.900
And it had a discount
rate equal to 1,

00:46:39.900 --> 00:46:46.025
or basically beta times
1 plus r equals 1.

00:46:46.025 --> 00:46:48.390
In the finite
horizon case, beta,

00:46:48.390 --> 00:46:51.540
that thing premultiplying
consumption,

00:46:51.540 --> 00:46:56.160
turns out if you stare
at it, is concave.

00:46:56.160 --> 00:47:00.610
We're already beginning to
anticipate these formulas

00:47:00.610 --> 00:47:02.940
and decreasing in t.

00:47:02.940 --> 00:47:05.310
And if you go back to
those two equations,

00:47:05.310 --> 00:47:08.050
you'll get kind of a
simplified version,

00:47:08.050 --> 00:47:11.190
that beta t times the
change in consumption

00:47:11.190 --> 00:47:17.730
is equal to this, quote,
"consumption innovation."

00:47:17.730 --> 00:47:20.410
And here's a formula for
the consumption innovation,

00:47:20.410 --> 00:47:27.620
which is, again, the
difference in expectation.

00:47:27.620 --> 00:47:31.650
So you're forecasting
the future all the time.

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:34.480
But you're also
getting these shocks.

00:47:34.480 --> 00:47:42.170
So as of t and t minus 1,
you were forecasting y t

00:47:42.170 --> 00:47:43.400
at t plus k.

00:47:43.400 --> 00:47:48.710
Sorry, y of t plus k, not either
to either, to t or t minus 1.

00:47:48.710 --> 00:47:50.360
It could be 10 years out.

00:47:50.360 --> 00:47:54.080
And you're constantly
adjusting your expectations,

00:47:54.080 --> 00:47:55.940
based on the current
information you

00:47:55.940 --> 00:47:57.500
have from the income process.

00:47:57.500 --> 00:47:59.900
And you're summing up over
all those future income

00:47:59.900 --> 00:48:06.380
shocks and discounting
backwards to get

00:48:06.380 --> 00:48:08.600
these, quote, "innovations."

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:16.700
So then imagine starting
this out at some date t

00:48:16.700 --> 00:48:22.340
equals 0, and then t equals
1, and t equals 2, and so on.

00:48:22.340 --> 00:48:24.650
And you could just
write out, literally,

00:48:24.650 --> 00:48:26.300
consumption in each
one of those dates.

00:48:29.310 --> 00:48:32.930
And of course, when you go
from one date to another,

00:48:32.930 --> 00:48:34.730
you get hit with this shock.

00:48:34.730 --> 00:48:37.430
And you're premultiplying
by the beta,

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:42.140
so you end up with this,
an explicit formula

00:48:42.140 --> 00:48:46.220
for consumption equal to
its initial given level.

00:48:46.220 --> 00:48:49.160
Plus, the beta moves
on the right-hand side,

00:48:49.160 --> 00:48:51.410
this sort of beta discounted.

00:48:51.410 --> 00:48:54.260
But it's not beta in
the preference function.

00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:58.040
This is that beta thing that
had to do with little t,

00:48:58.040 --> 00:49:00.350
big T, and all of
that, that took

00:49:00.350 --> 00:49:03.010
care of the lifecycle
considerations.

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:09.910
So finally, we see
again the familiar theme

00:49:09.910 --> 00:49:14.170
that the variance
at t is related

00:49:14.170 --> 00:49:17.170
to the initial cross-sectional
variance at zero,

00:49:17.170 --> 00:49:21.250
plus the sum of variance terms.

00:49:24.490 --> 00:49:28.000
So the issue-- so
roughly speaking,

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:32.470
it looks like, yeah, it ought
to increase-- unless you retire

00:49:32.470 --> 00:49:34.680
and you have no more
things then forecast,

00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:37.120
then this piece goes away.

00:49:37.120 --> 00:49:41.910
But before that happens,
you're looking at future

00:49:41.910 --> 00:49:44.920
and making expectations
of future income.

00:49:44.920 --> 00:49:48.120
So you just keep adding on.

00:49:48.120 --> 00:49:51.000
So that's why inequality
is increasing in the data,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.010
through the lens
of these models.

00:49:53.010 --> 00:50:00.030
And then the issue is, is it
linear or concave or convex?

00:50:00.030 --> 00:50:01.980
That has to do with
this beta and also

00:50:01.980 --> 00:50:08.690
has to do with what we
can infer about sigma,

00:50:08.690 --> 00:50:10.550
about the consumption
innovations.

00:50:19.070 --> 00:50:24.100
So in response to
your question, if we

00:50:24.100 --> 00:50:27.130
assume this
innovation is entirely

00:50:27.130 --> 00:50:32.050
white noise, normalized
by the interest rate,

00:50:32.050 --> 00:50:35.560
then sigma square eta
at t is a constant

00:50:35.560 --> 00:50:37.000
that doesn't depend on t.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:41.470
And this is the
resulting expression

00:50:41.470 --> 00:50:43.700
with the sigma square
eta pulled out front.

00:50:43.700 --> 00:50:49.030
And then the
convexity is entirely

00:50:49.030 --> 00:50:52.720
due to this beta
thing, which if you

00:50:52.720 --> 00:50:57.130
start taking some derivatives
and so on, it's a bit messy.

00:50:57.130 --> 00:51:01.930
You can convince yourself
that that thing is convex.

00:51:01.930 --> 00:51:04.710
Here's an orthogonal example.

00:51:04.710 --> 00:51:06.460
I guess, [? Jan, ?] I
jumped the gun a bit

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:08.800
because this actually
allows something a bit

00:51:08.800 --> 00:51:13.180
different, which is this
autoregressive thing.

00:51:13.180 --> 00:51:15.430
This is IID, and then
this is autoregressive,

00:51:15.430 --> 00:51:20.260
so this income
process is persistent.

00:51:27.470 --> 00:51:31.760
It's a bit odd because this
was the innovation that had

00:51:31.760 --> 00:51:38.210
to do with the innovation to--

00:51:38.210 --> 00:51:40.970
the right-hand side had to
do with all those expectation

00:51:40.970 --> 00:51:41.640
differences.

00:51:41.640 --> 00:51:44.640
So it's like, let's just assume
it looks something like this.

00:51:44.640 --> 00:51:48.020
This is more explicit
about the income process.

00:51:48.020 --> 00:51:50.750
And you can derive the
formula for the change

00:51:50.750 --> 00:51:55.210
in consumption, where this
beta r thing is now this mess.

00:51:57.920 --> 00:52:05.330
And it turns out,
this will be concave

00:52:05.330 --> 00:52:08.320
if you can sign this expression.

00:52:08.320 --> 00:52:11.480
And it may also be
decreasing in age

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:16.580
if this is true, and so
actually, except for some days

00:52:16.580 --> 00:52:17.780
of theta, both things--

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:26.050
So two of those three
countries, the profile

00:52:26.050 --> 00:52:28.450
was, say, not concave.

00:52:28.450 --> 00:52:31.750
It could have been linear, which
is a weak case of concavity,

00:52:31.750 --> 00:52:33.580
or even convex.

00:52:33.580 --> 00:52:37.240
And so basically, then
you could rule this out

00:52:37.240 --> 00:52:38.770
because these are--

00:52:38.770 --> 00:52:41.110
this kind of persistence
would give you concavity.

00:52:41.110 --> 00:52:42.160
But you don't see that.

00:52:46.990 --> 00:52:49.870
But then we have
the sort of paradox

00:52:49.870 --> 00:52:55.910
that something like these
white noise processes

00:52:55.910 --> 00:52:57.680
must be closer to
the truth if we're

00:52:57.680 --> 00:52:59.660
going to get convex profiles.

00:52:59.660 --> 00:53:05.090
But that's an assumption
about the income process.

00:53:05.090 --> 00:53:09.720
And in particular,
one way to get it

00:53:09.720 --> 00:53:14.650
is to say that there's a large
stationary component to income.

00:53:14.650 --> 00:53:20.620
So you're not getting those
innovations in your forecasts.

00:53:20.620 --> 00:53:24.460
And we don't see
that in the data.

00:53:24.460 --> 00:53:27.200
Income profiles
are not stationary.

00:53:27.200 --> 00:53:31.050
There's heavy
lifecycle components.

00:53:38.700 --> 00:53:42.190
So nothing's perfect, I guess.

00:53:42.190 --> 00:53:45.100
Every model is a benchmark.

00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:46.810
Almost every model
is going to deliver

00:53:46.810 --> 00:53:48.430
something that might fit well.

00:53:48.430 --> 00:53:52.450
Otherwise, we're probably
not reading it in a journal.

00:53:52.450 --> 00:53:56.260
Or it may actually
also generate things

00:53:56.260 --> 00:53:58.080
that are not consistent
with the data,

00:53:58.080 --> 00:54:01.300
and if you're a good scholar,
you're reporting that too.

00:54:05.790 --> 00:54:10.020
What about the permanent
income and the dispersion

00:54:10.020 --> 00:54:10.965
of income by age?

00:54:16.740 --> 00:54:20.090
So again, disposable
income takes

00:54:20.090 --> 00:54:28.300
on this form, which is
sort of asset return

00:54:28.300 --> 00:54:30.520
stream, plus income.

00:54:30.520 --> 00:54:32.920
And then you use it for
consumption and savings,

00:54:32.920 --> 00:54:36.430
adjusting for where you
are in the life cycle.

00:54:36.430 --> 00:54:37.990
Or you could take
the difference.

00:54:37.990 --> 00:54:40.420
Savings is the
difference between income

00:54:40.420 --> 00:54:44.140
and this beta-adjusted
consumption.

00:54:44.140 --> 00:54:48.710
And some of these models
you can get a closed form

00:54:48.710 --> 00:54:53.210
expression for savings, namely
the so-called Campbell's "rainy

00:54:53.210 --> 00:54:59.960
day," which is really
kind of cool, which is you

00:54:59.960 --> 00:55:05.450
save enough at t to be able
to cover the discounted

00:55:05.450 --> 00:55:10.700
shortfalls in sort of
these earnings innovations.

00:55:14.140 --> 00:55:16.900
So you want to smooth those out.

00:55:16.900 --> 00:55:20.310
And you save just enough
to do that in expectation.

00:55:24.110 --> 00:55:30.010
Anyway, so we're rewriting
disposable income

00:55:30.010 --> 00:55:31.750
equal to the savings component.

00:55:31.750 --> 00:55:37.410
We already had that,
less the savings--

00:55:37.410 --> 00:55:39.120
plus the savings component.

00:55:39.120 --> 00:55:42.450
Sorry, I get confused
because savings was negative.

00:55:42.450 --> 00:55:46.200
It used to be here,
and now it's out here.

00:55:46.200 --> 00:55:49.170
Savings is not negative,
but these innovations

00:55:49.170 --> 00:55:53.340
are negative because you
save to cover shortfalls.

00:55:53.340 --> 00:55:55.170
And then you get
implications here

00:55:55.170 --> 00:56:00.528
for if one thing
is a random walk,

00:56:00.528 --> 00:56:02.070
and the other thing
is a random walk,

00:56:02.070 --> 00:56:04.070
then the sum of two things
that are random walks

00:56:04.070 --> 00:56:05.430
is also a random walk.

00:56:10.910 --> 00:56:16.410
So basically, savings ought to
be stationary in that sense.

00:56:16.410 --> 00:56:18.500
And it ought to be
dispersing at the rate

00:56:18.500 --> 00:56:21.720
that consumption is dispersing.

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:23.900
And they don't see that
in the data either.

00:56:27.760 --> 00:56:33.030
And in particular,
earnings is dispersing,

00:56:33.030 --> 00:56:37.680
which is a point that was made
on the other slide as well.

00:56:42.810 --> 00:56:45.890
And then finally,
I guess this is

00:56:45.890 --> 00:56:49.550
like the fourth version
of something that starts

00:56:49.550 --> 00:56:51.110
to look like the same thing.

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:57.470
Most of those
analytic expressions

00:56:57.470 --> 00:56:59.720
were assuming something
like quadratic utility.

00:56:59.720 --> 00:57:03.560
That's how you managed to get
this really tight reduced form

00:57:03.560 --> 00:57:05.480
analytic expression.

00:57:05.480 --> 00:57:07.910
If you don't do that, if you
have constant relative risk

00:57:07.910 --> 00:57:12.500
aversion, for example, or a
more general utility function,

00:57:12.500 --> 00:57:15.580
than the Euler
equation basically

00:57:15.580 --> 00:57:23.150
is going to equate the marginal
utility today to something

00:57:23.150 --> 00:57:24.710
like marginal utility tomorrow.

00:57:32.546 --> 00:57:36.030
We might say, well, where's
the expectation operator?

00:57:36.030 --> 00:57:39.190
Instead, the shock is put over
here on the right-hand side.

00:57:39.190 --> 00:57:42.300
So this is like
an Euler equation.

00:57:42.300 --> 00:57:45.670
If this were 0, and
the interest rate

00:57:45.670 --> 00:57:49.610
was equal to this
delta discount rate,

00:57:49.610 --> 00:57:53.290
then basically the marginal
utility of consumption,

00:57:53.290 --> 00:58:00.240
if we could deduce it,
would be not going anywhere.

00:58:00.240 --> 00:58:04.450
It would be the same over time.

00:58:04.450 --> 00:58:09.490
But again, with
r equal to delta,

00:58:09.490 --> 00:58:12.220
we kick on this extra
orthogonal shock,

00:58:12.220 --> 00:58:15.820
which makes the marginal utility
of consumption dispersing

00:58:15.820 --> 00:58:18.580
in the future, relative today.

00:58:18.580 --> 00:58:21.310
And you can even
have r not equal

00:58:21.310 --> 00:58:25.720
to delta, as long as
delta is greater than r.

00:58:25.720 --> 00:58:31.050
The same logic applies
because you've kind of like

00:58:31.050 --> 00:58:35.390
amplified this thing, carrying
it through to tomorrow,

00:58:35.390 --> 00:58:37.420
along with the u shock.

00:58:44.650 --> 00:58:47.430
So that's another way to get
at the variance of consumption

00:58:47.430 --> 00:58:53.850
increasing, depending on what
you assume about the utility

00:58:53.850 --> 00:58:55.080
function.

00:58:55.080 --> 00:59:03.110
Some functions, though, have
a force that go the other way.

00:59:03.110 --> 00:59:06.650
In particular, if you're
really, really into it,

00:59:06.650 --> 00:59:11.080
you get into third derivatives.

00:59:11.080 --> 00:59:15.100
But when you're really
sort of cautious,

00:59:15.100 --> 00:59:21.200
that lambda is convex.

00:59:21.200 --> 00:59:25.610
So you're taking a second
derivative of already

00:59:25.610 --> 00:59:26.650
the marginal utility.

00:59:26.650 --> 00:59:29.500
That's why I commented about
third derivatives of utility

00:59:29.500 --> 00:59:30.970
functions.

00:59:30.970 --> 00:59:34.610
And that, if you start
staring at this thing,

00:59:34.610 --> 00:59:40.580
can actually push you back
against this dispersion

00:59:40.580 --> 00:59:41.854
of consumption.

00:59:58.160 --> 01:00:01.990
So I'm having a sense that
this is going on and on.

01:00:01.990 --> 01:00:05.170
But the point is to take each
of these different forces

01:00:05.170 --> 01:00:08.140
and then tell stories about
what must be true in Taiwan,

01:00:08.140 --> 01:00:12.680
versus Britain,
versus the US, to try

01:00:12.680 --> 01:00:18.970
to rationalize what
we're seeing in the data,

01:00:18.970 --> 01:00:20.380
and similarly, here.

01:00:25.980 --> 01:00:29.220
So let's just say three words
about excess smoothness.

01:00:33.270 --> 01:00:35.610
To repeat, the
lifecycle model implies

01:00:35.610 --> 01:00:38.550
that shocks to permanent income
should be fully incorporated

01:00:38.550 --> 01:00:44.150
into consumption,
while innovations

01:00:44.150 --> 01:00:48.335
to the transitory part are not.

01:00:54.870 --> 01:00:57.240
Basically, all the income--

01:00:57.240 --> 01:00:59.890
all the transitory
income fluctuations

01:00:59.890 --> 01:01:03.837
should not be appearing in
consumption, which actually

01:01:03.837 --> 01:01:05.670
is something we've
talked about with regards

01:01:05.670 --> 01:01:07.590
to the full risk-sharing
model, except there,

01:01:07.590 --> 01:01:10.080
we didn't make this
distinction between

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:11.960
transitory and permanent.

01:01:15.960 --> 01:01:18.750
But when they go and
look at the data,

01:01:18.750 --> 01:01:21.280
they say, hey,
consumption is too smooth.

01:01:21.280 --> 01:01:25.950
It doesn't react to innovations
in the permanent component.

01:01:25.950 --> 01:01:29.505
And other people have
found something similar.

01:01:32.450 --> 01:01:35.920
And we're inching
forward to models

01:01:35.920 --> 01:01:38.120
where we're going to need
to modify the models.

01:01:38.120 --> 01:01:40.120
We're going to have to
introduce something else,

01:01:40.120 --> 01:01:45.640
like private information,
and more on that in a second.

01:01:53.290 --> 01:01:54.290
Yup?

01:01:54.290 --> 01:01:55.790
AUDIENCE: Why do
all these assume

01:01:55.790 --> 01:01:58.110
the market is incomplete?

01:01:58.110 --> 01:02:01.590
So maybe just because the
market is relatively complete,

01:02:01.590 --> 01:02:04.698
so these [INAUDIBLE]?

01:02:04.698 --> 01:02:06.490
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So
that's my gut reaction.

01:02:09.380 --> 01:02:15.580
Actually, so this
Pavoni paper puts

01:02:15.580 --> 01:02:22.280
in sort of some unobserved
savings and other things.

01:02:22.280 --> 01:02:24.880
And it actually comes
close to the data.

01:02:24.880 --> 01:02:28.930
So it isn't all the way
toward full insurance,

01:02:28.930 --> 01:02:33.670
but it is more full insurance
than what these models imply.

01:02:36.260 --> 01:02:38.440
So it's trying to
reconcile the puzzle.

01:02:42.350 --> 01:02:45.335
I'd like to think
I'm quite agnostic.

01:02:48.860 --> 01:02:52.310
In my rural [? Thai ?]
data, certainly,

01:02:52.310 --> 01:02:54.920
when you include other variables
and not just consumption,

01:02:54.920 --> 01:02:56.870
we see rejections of
full risk-sharing.

01:02:56.870 --> 01:02:59.000
I'm not determined
to always find

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:01.160
full risk-sharing in the data.

01:03:01.160 --> 01:03:05.580
But likewise, I would hope
these guys aren't clinging

01:03:05.580 --> 01:03:08.430
to the permanent income model
as the only game in town,

01:03:08.430 --> 01:03:11.700
because it's clearly
also suffering

01:03:11.700 --> 01:03:17.370
from its own sort of anomalies,
relative to the data.

01:03:19.927 --> 01:03:21.510
And there's no reason
to think that it

01:03:21.510 --> 01:03:28.095
has to be this same model for
every village or every country,

01:03:28.095 --> 01:03:29.790
and actually,
Deaton and Paxson's

01:03:29.790 --> 01:03:31.650
stuff, looking at the
cross sections, kind

01:03:31.650 --> 01:03:33.000
of saying that it's different.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:34.833
It could be different
in different countries

01:03:34.833 --> 01:03:37.470
if you're going to try
to reconcile the observed

01:03:37.470 --> 01:03:38.473
movements.

01:03:43.570 --> 01:03:46.180
But anyway, you guys need to
know about this literature.

01:03:49.390 --> 01:03:53.170
You need to have a view of the
different consumption smoothing

01:03:53.170 --> 01:03:54.370
literature.

01:03:54.370 --> 01:04:00.750
I guess I should
also say sort of,

01:04:00.750 --> 01:04:06.270
it looks as though it's a
macro-ish, US-ish literature.

01:04:06.270 --> 01:04:09.960
But that's not true, certainly,
for Paxson and Deaton, who

01:04:09.960 --> 01:04:15.040
are avid development economists
and looking at that data

01:04:15.040 --> 01:04:16.330
from developing countries.

01:04:16.330 --> 01:04:19.420
And likewise, the initial
risk-sharing stuff,

01:04:19.420 --> 01:04:21.370
that wasn't peculiar
to development.

01:04:21.370 --> 01:04:23.830
That was being tested
by Cochrane and Mace

01:04:23.830 --> 01:04:26.050
and so on in US data.

01:04:26.050 --> 01:04:30.040
So there's really
never been this idea

01:04:30.040 --> 01:04:34.780
that somehow macro is in one
room, using one subset of data,

01:04:34.780 --> 01:04:38.650
and micro is another room,
using another subset.

01:04:38.650 --> 01:04:40.360
That would be rather silly.

01:04:40.360 --> 01:04:44.760
So we really need to know
how all these models work.

01:04:54.300 --> 01:04:57.690
So this is, again, Campbell's
saving for a rainy day.

01:05:01.055 --> 01:05:02.930
It's repeated because
it's a different paper.

01:05:06.750 --> 01:05:07.950
They look at--

01:05:07.950 --> 01:05:14.330
Campbell and Deaton now
are looking at US data

01:05:14.330 --> 01:05:16.370
and saying the labor
income is described

01:05:16.370 --> 01:05:22.280
by this autoregressive
process with a positive serial

01:05:22.280 --> 01:05:23.120
correlation.

01:05:26.890 --> 01:05:31.740
And what that means is
innovations are, quote unquote,

01:05:31.740 --> 01:05:34.680
"more than permanent,"
not just random walk-ish,

01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:36.770
but basically--

01:05:36.770 --> 01:05:38.670
Now you get even
into more trouble

01:05:38.670 --> 01:05:41.880
because if consumption should
reflect the innovations

01:05:41.880 --> 01:05:44.370
to permanent income, and
what you see in innovations

01:05:44.370 --> 01:05:47.910
is more than permanent,
that means consumption

01:05:47.910 --> 01:05:51.090
should respond even more.

01:05:51.090 --> 01:05:54.660
And it's not, in the data,
responding that much.

01:05:54.660 --> 01:05:58.080
It's much less variable.

01:05:58.080 --> 01:06:00.090
So either they're
getting this fact wrong.

01:06:00.090 --> 01:06:07.440
Or, again, maybe the households
have more information somehow.

01:06:07.440 --> 01:06:12.690
Or they have stupid
expectations or whatever.

01:06:12.690 --> 01:06:16.470
These guys were not able
to resolve the puzzle.

01:06:16.470 --> 01:06:18.520
If you want to see the
equations, there they are.

01:06:18.520 --> 01:06:21.720
I'm not sure at this point
that it adds all that much

01:06:21.720 --> 01:06:23.442
more to the discussion.

01:06:29.850 --> 01:06:33.380
And this is what I was saying
about Attanasio and Pavoni.

01:06:37.460 --> 01:06:42.642
So the plan is--

01:06:42.642 --> 01:06:44.100
there's a little
more coming today.

01:06:44.100 --> 01:06:45.870
Don't worry.

01:06:45.870 --> 01:06:49.190
Or you might say, oh, darn.

01:06:49.190 --> 01:06:51.630
But the plan in the
ordering of the lectures

01:06:51.630 --> 01:06:58.050
is to do labor
and wage variation

01:06:58.050 --> 01:07:03.090
and smoothing, adding labor
supply to a consumption model,

01:07:03.090 --> 01:07:07.230
and talk about elasticities
and sensitivities.

01:07:07.230 --> 01:07:10.110
That will be done with both
the full risk-sharing model,

01:07:10.110 --> 01:07:14.580
as well as a version of these
incomplete market models.

01:07:14.580 --> 01:07:18.450
So we'll see what survives,
depending on what you assume

01:07:18.450 --> 01:07:20.400
about the market structure.

01:07:20.400 --> 01:07:25.200
And then we're going to go to
have a whole lecture on models

01:07:25.200 --> 01:07:29.910
that are much more explicit
about moral hazard, unobserved

01:07:29.910 --> 01:07:34.120
income, and so on.

01:07:34.120 --> 01:07:38.760
And this Pavoni paper is one
of them in that literature.

01:07:38.760 --> 01:07:41.070
We're not going to
cover it in class.

01:07:48.670 --> 01:07:57.200
So actually, the front part of
the lecture was about this BPP.

01:07:57.200 --> 01:08:00.730
It's probably a bit
mysterious what it was,

01:08:00.730 --> 01:08:02.620
so we can review
that for a second.

01:08:05.730 --> 01:08:19.729
The idea is that you
postulate that log of earnings

01:08:19.729 --> 01:08:24.200
takes on this process where
x is a vector of shocks,

01:08:24.200 --> 01:08:30.609
a is some vector
of coefficients,

01:08:30.609 --> 01:08:38.420
the shocks are IID, the x's
are, and they have variances.

01:08:41.410 --> 01:08:46.130
This allows a whole bunch of
stuff, not only just random

01:08:46.130 --> 01:08:52.140
walks, but autoregressive
integrated moving

01:08:52.140 --> 01:08:56.340
average processes on income.

01:08:56.340 --> 01:08:58.609
This is what you see.

01:08:58.609 --> 01:09:00.899
And then this
general formulation

01:09:00.899 --> 01:09:06.779
allows a bunch of different
specifications, which they're

01:09:06.779 --> 01:09:08.010
going to try to estimate.

01:09:15.519 --> 01:09:18.520
And somehow what
they want to back out

01:09:18.520 --> 01:09:21.609
is this insurance coefficient.

01:09:21.609 --> 01:09:25.090
So here's, again, how it's
easy to get turned around.

01:09:25.090 --> 01:09:28.210
This is how a sort of,
like, quote unquote,

01:09:28.210 --> 01:09:31.479
a regression coefficient
of how consumption

01:09:31.479 --> 01:09:37.370
is moving with this particular
shock, inferred somehow.

01:09:37.370 --> 01:09:42.910
But 1 minus that is then
the degree of insurance

01:09:42.910 --> 01:09:46.630
because when consumption
doesn't move with that shock,

01:09:46.630 --> 01:09:47.819
this is zero.

01:09:47.819 --> 01:09:51.670
And so insurance is like,
perfect, measured at 1.

01:09:58.460 --> 01:10:01.430
And you could put
t's on these things

01:10:01.430 --> 01:10:08.030
if you sort the data by
age, which came up earlier.

01:10:17.400 --> 01:10:24.630
So we don't really see
all those permanent

01:10:24.630 --> 01:10:26.385
versus transitory shocks.

01:10:29.430 --> 01:10:31.635
You kind of have to
infer them, somehow.

01:10:35.820 --> 01:10:50.810
And this is a bit like
using some assumed function

01:10:50.810 --> 01:10:57.360
on the income process,
and then filtering

01:10:57.360 --> 01:11:02.328
the data through that function
and looking at the covariance

01:11:02.328 --> 01:11:03.120
with income change.

01:11:06.370 --> 01:11:08.070
But they don't just
do three alone,

01:11:08.070 --> 01:11:15.590
because this would be a
statement about income alone.

01:11:15.590 --> 01:11:22.360
They jointly estimate this
function, g, essentially,

01:11:22.360 --> 01:11:23.830
jointly with consumption.

01:11:48.890 --> 01:11:55.120
So for example, if
you assume income

01:11:55.120 --> 01:11:58.690
took on this classic form
that we were actually

01:11:58.690 --> 01:12:01.930
tracking through the
lectures, then income

01:12:01.930 --> 01:12:09.430
would be the sum of a random
walk with its own innovation

01:12:09.430 --> 01:12:12.400
and variance and
epsilon, which would

01:12:12.400 --> 01:12:18.780
be this IID transitory shock.

01:12:18.780 --> 01:12:22.820
If you believe this to be the
structure, and there are many,

01:12:22.820 --> 01:12:27.520
many other candidates, then
you take a first difference.

01:12:27.520 --> 01:12:31.510
And by construction
then, what would be left

01:12:31.510 --> 01:12:38.420
would be this innovation in
the permanent part and a time

01:12:38.420 --> 01:12:41.360
difference in the
transitory part, which

01:12:41.360 --> 01:12:42.680
is still transitory.

01:12:47.600 --> 01:12:49.990
So then the consumption
model tells you about--

01:12:54.910 --> 01:13:03.420
puts restrictions on how
the change in consumption

01:13:03.420 --> 01:13:15.360
should be responding, basically
taking advantage of the time

01:13:15.360 --> 01:13:15.930
delays.

01:13:15.930 --> 01:13:19.500
As you go back like,
two, three periods,

01:13:19.500 --> 01:13:22.020
there is nothing that
happened that far back that's

01:13:22.020 --> 01:13:24.550
influencing anything
at all today.

01:13:24.550 --> 01:13:29.640
So those past data kind of
become predetermined variables,

01:13:29.640 --> 01:13:31.390
almost as if they
were instruments.

01:13:31.390 --> 01:13:39.150
And so that kind of mysterious
notation about g on y, this

01:13:39.150 --> 01:13:42.960
is a version of it,
postulating a model

01:13:42.960 --> 01:13:47.400
and then going back far
enough time, so you would see,

01:13:47.400 --> 01:13:49.650
basically, zero covariance.

01:14:00.220 --> 01:14:01.570
So here it is, actually.

01:14:01.570 --> 01:14:08.110
This g is just basically
the time difference

01:14:08.110 --> 01:14:12.990
in income at t plus 1.

01:14:15.880 --> 01:14:20.590
And given the other
assumptions they make,

01:14:20.590 --> 01:14:25.700
you back out some of the
key things that you want.

01:14:25.700 --> 01:14:27.950
For example, how on
earth are we going

01:14:27.950 --> 01:14:30.290
to know about the variance
of the transitory shocks

01:14:30.290 --> 01:14:34.340
if we never see
transitory shocks?

01:14:34.340 --> 01:14:38.930
Basically, that turns out to be
the covariance of two things we

01:14:38.930 --> 01:14:43.700
do see, the time difference
of consumption at income at t

01:14:43.700 --> 01:14:47.852
and the time difference
of income at t plus 1.

01:14:47.852 --> 01:14:49.310
Hopefully, you're
seeing the spirit

01:14:49.310 --> 01:14:54.442
of this, if not following
every line of the algebra.

01:14:54.442 --> 01:14:55.900
So that's where we
get that object.

01:14:59.250 --> 01:15:00.860
And how would you
get the variance

01:15:00.860 --> 01:15:03.410
of the permanent income
part, the innovation

01:15:03.410 --> 01:15:05.350
to permanent income?

01:15:05.350 --> 01:15:09.210
Remember, that thing is
persisting over time.

01:15:09.210 --> 01:15:11.540
So it's a bit more complicated.

01:15:14.110 --> 01:15:20.660
It turns out to be this
daunting object, which

01:15:20.660 --> 01:15:23.090
is to-- and everything
here you see.

01:15:23.090 --> 01:15:24.260
That's point number one.

01:15:24.260 --> 01:15:26.540
It's the covariance of the
time difference of income

01:15:26.540 --> 01:15:33.530
at t, against the sum of the
changes in income at t minus 1,

01:15:33.530 --> 01:15:35.730
t and t plus 1.

01:15:35.730 --> 01:15:41.600
So there, again, you see this
sort of time structure at work.

01:15:41.600 --> 01:15:45.640
The spirit of it is go
back far enough in time

01:15:45.640 --> 01:15:47.440
so everything is predetermined.

01:15:51.580 --> 01:15:53.710
And this is the
covariance of consumption

01:15:53.710 --> 01:15:55.900
with that permanent shock.

01:15:55.900 --> 01:15:58.290
So this is a key object.

01:15:58.290 --> 01:16:01.210
Remember, that insurance formula
is, how much is consumption

01:16:01.210 --> 01:16:06.780
moving with the innovation
to permanent income?

01:16:06.780 --> 01:16:12.190
It all seems quite mysterious,
but here is an explicit formula

01:16:12.190 --> 01:16:13.440
for how they get it.

01:16:16.170 --> 01:16:20.130
So clearly, it's a
linear model, using

01:16:20.130 --> 01:16:22.260
a lot of these variance
covariance formulas,

01:16:22.260 --> 01:16:25.682
given the assumed structure.

01:16:25.682 --> 01:16:27.390
They don't have to--
their starting point

01:16:27.390 --> 01:16:30.960
could have been something else.

01:16:30.960 --> 01:16:33.150
As I said, you had
these ARIMA processes,

01:16:33.150 --> 01:16:35.070
but it is some structure.

01:16:35.070 --> 01:16:39.660
When you specify the order
of the moving average part

01:16:39.660 --> 01:16:42.690
and the order of the
autoregressive part,

01:16:42.690 --> 01:16:44.280
you get restrictions
on the data.

01:16:47.730 --> 01:16:52.400
So hopefully that helps
resolve some of the mysteries

01:16:52.400 --> 01:16:57.750
about what this BPP algorithm
and what they do to the data

01:16:57.750 --> 01:17:01.320
to measure these insurance
against idiosyncratic and

01:17:01.320 --> 01:17:03.780
permanent shocks.

01:17:03.780 --> 01:17:05.280
So I'm going to
leave for [? Whit ?]

01:17:05.280 --> 01:17:13.010
to do the version of smoothing,
a bit in the Italian data.

01:17:13.010 --> 01:17:16.410
But I will just say,
by way of motivation,

01:17:16.410 --> 01:17:19.490
it's again looking
at various models,

01:17:19.490 --> 01:17:21.860
although they're
not exactly nested,

01:17:21.860 --> 01:17:26.150
and looking at the
responses of consumption

01:17:26.150 --> 01:17:32.330
to innovations, but also
of wealth to innovations.

01:17:32.330 --> 01:17:37.220
So we saw in my data sort of
how wealth in various lectures

01:17:37.220 --> 01:17:39.260
is moving around in
the cross section

01:17:39.260 --> 01:17:41.990
and moving around over time.

01:17:41.990 --> 01:17:44.180
We talked about
responses to shocks

01:17:44.180 --> 01:17:48.110
and whether they're using
savings accounts and so on.

01:17:48.110 --> 01:17:52.490
So these guys in their own way
are doing something similar.

01:17:52.490 --> 01:17:57.470
And the paper backs
out the movements

01:17:57.470 --> 01:17:59.930
in consumption and
wealth that are predicted

01:17:59.930 --> 01:18:01.670
from certain kinds
of innovations,

01:18:01.670 --> 01:18:05.450
but not just between this year
and next year, but this year

01:18:05.450 --> 01:18:09.210
and two years from now, all
the way up to six years,

01:18:09.210 --> 01:18:10.590
or even longer.

01:18:10.590 --> 01:18:14.240
So you kind of get the
sort of time profiles

01:18:14.240 --> 01:18:16.090
of responsiveness.

01:18:16.090 --> 01:18:20.030
And very much in the spirit of
what we're talking about today,

01:18:20.030 --> 01:18:23.382
yet again, a bit different,
those response patterns

01:18:23.382 --> 01:18:25.340
are very different,
depending on whether you're

01:18:25.340 --> 01:18:30.390
talking about the permanent
income model or the life cycle

01:18:30.390 --> 01:18:32.180
buffer stock type model.

